value.value: Phenotype only expressed under conditions where calorie intake is restricted.

Phenotype that is any abnormality in cell migration (GO:0016477). 'cell migration' is defined as: 'The controlled self-propelled movement of a cell from one site to a destination guided by molecular cues.'
Phenotype that is an increase in any kind of rate (e.g. speed, frequency) of cell growth (GO:0016049) in a whole animal or in some specific organ tissue or clone of cells compared to wild-type.
Phenotype that is an decrease in any kind of rate (e.g. speed, frequency) of cell growth (GO:0016049) in a whole animal or in some specific organ tissue or clone of cells compared to wild-type.
Phenotype that is a decrease in size of an initially normally sized organ or tissue due to wasting away of cells.

Phenotype that is any abnormality or in or absence of a jump response (GO:0007630). The jump response in Drosophila is a reflex escape response that can be triggered by a number of signals including odor and light. Standard assays are commonly used to test odor and light induced jump response.

Phenotype that is any abnormality in mating behavior (GO:0007617). 'mating behavior' is defined as: 'The behavioral interactions between organisms for the purpose of mating, or sexual reproduction resulting in the formation of zygotes.'
A clone of somatic cells that share a mutant genotype that includes being Minute +/+ and that is part of and derived from an animal with a different genotype that includes being Minute +/-.
Phenotype that consists of abnormal growth of a tissue or organ due to increased numbers of cells, but in which the affected tissue or organ does not maintain its normal form.
Phenotype that is a reduction in size of an organ or tissue compared to wild-type due to reduced numbers of cells being produced during its development or growth.

definition.value: This term should not be used where an organ or tissue is reduced in size due to the wasting away of existing cells.

value.value: Phenotype that is any abnormality in response to oxidative stress (GO:0006979). 'response to oxidative stress' is defined as: 'Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, e.g. superoxide anions, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and hydroxyl radicals.'
Expressed in virgin females.

definition.value: May be used as a qualifier for gene or transgene expression or phenotype. Note - its use does not imply expression (of gene or phenotype) exclusively in virgin females.

value.value: Expressed in mated females.

definition.value: May be used as a qualifier for gene or transgene expression or phenotype. Note - its use does not imply expression (of gene or phenotype) exclusively in mated females.

value.value: Expressed in virgin males.

definition.value: May be used as a qualifier for gene or transgene expression or phenotype. Note - its use does not imply expression (of gene or phenotype) exclusively in virgin males.

value.value: Expressed in mated males.

definition.value: May be used as a qualifier for gene or transgene expression or phenotype. Note - its use does not imply expression (of gene or phenotype) exclusively in mated females.

value.value: Expression is limited to virgin females.

definition.value: May be used to qualify expression of phenotypes or of genes, transgenes etc.

value.value: Expression is limited to mated females.

definition.value: May be used to qualify expression of phenotypes or of genes, transgenes etc.

value.value: Expression is limited to mated males.

definition.value: May be used to qualify expression of phenotypes or of genes, transgenes etc.

value.value: Expression is limited to virgin males.

definition.value: May be used to qualify expression of phenotypes or of genes, transgenes etc.

value.value: Embryonic/larval segmentation phenotype that is the complete or partial loss of terminal regions of the embryo/larva: the acron, telson and immediately adjacent segments.
A nitrosamine that is N-ethylethanamine substituted by a nitroso group at the N-atom (from CHEBI).
An allele that completely lacks function (i.e. whose gene productive is completely inactive) at high temperatures, but that retains at least some function at lower temperatures.

label.value: temperature conditional amorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred to completely lack function at some temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not others (permissive temperatures) from the observation that addition of extra copies in the genome has no effect on the phenotype at the restrictive temperatures. Most commonly, evidence takes the form of the observation that the phenotype of homozygotes (2 copies) is identical to that seen when the allele is in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy).

A publication that is not issued on a regular, ongoing basis containing separate articles or chapters (typically reviews) written by different authors on a single subject or related subjects, overseen by one or more editors.
An allele that completely lacks function (i.e. whose gene productive is completely inactive) at some temperatures, but not others.

label.value: cold sensitive amorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred to completely lack function at low temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at high temperatures (permissive temperatures) from the observation that adding extra copies in the genome has no effect on the phenotype at the restrictive temperatures. Most commonly, evidence takes the form of the observation that the phenotype of homozygotes (2 copies) is identical to that seen when the allele is in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy).

label.value: heat sensitive amorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred to completely lack function at high temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at low temperatures (permissive temperatures) from the observation that adding extra copies in the genome has no effect on the phenotype at the restrictive temperatures. Most commonly, evidence takes the form of the observation that the phenotype of homozygotes (2 copies) is identical to that seen when the allele is in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy).

label.value: cold sensitive amorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to completely lack function at low temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at high temperatures (permissive temperatures).

label.value: heat sensitive amorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to completely lack function at high temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at low temperatures (permissive temperatures).

label.value: temperature conditional amorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to completely lack function at some temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at others (permissive temperatures).

label.value: temperature conditional loss of function allele

value.value: An allele that at some temperatures but not others either makes no functional gene product or makes reduced levels of a normally functioning gene product or makes a gene product with reduced activity compared to wild-type.

label.value: heat sensitive loss of function allele

value.value: An allele that at high temperatures but not low temperatures, either makes no functional gene product, makes reduced levels of a normally functioning gene product or makes a gene product with reduced activity compared to wild-type.

label.value: cold sensitive loss of function allele

value.value: An allele that at low temperatures but not high temperatures, either makes no functional gene product, makes reduced levels of a normally functioning gene product or makes a gene product with reduced activity compared to wild-type.

label.value: temperature conditional gain of function allele

value.value: An allele that at some temperatures but not others, either makes a normally functioning gene product but at higher levels or in a different spatial or temporal pattern to wild-type, or a product with increased or novel activity compared to wild-type.

label.value: heat sensitive gain of function allele

value.value: An allele that at high temperatures but not low temperatures, either makes a normally functioning gene product but at higher levels or in a different spatial or temporal pattern to wild-type, or a product with increased or novel activity compared to wild-type.

label.value: cold sensitive gain of function allele

value.value: An allele that at low temperatures but not high temperatures, either makes a normally functioning gene product but at higher levels or in a different spatial or temporal pattern to wild-type, or a product with increased or novel activity compared to wild-type.
An allele that, at some temperatures but not others, makes a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity.

An allele that makes a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but which at high temperatures is present in a lesser amount or with lowered activity, and that retains normal levels of expression or activity at low temperatures.

An allele that makes a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but which at low temperatures is present in a lesser amount or with lowered activity, and that retains normal function at higher temperatures.

label.value: temperature conditional hypomorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred from genetic evidence to have normal activity at some temperatures (permissive temperatures) but at other temperatures to make a gene product with normal function but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity (non-permissive temperatures). The genetic evidence must consist of an observation extra copies in the genome decrease the expressivity and/or penetrance of the phenotype at non-permissive temperatures. Most commonly this evidence takes the form of experiments showing that the homozygote (2 copies) has a weaker phenotype at non-permissive temperatures than the allele in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy)).

label.value: cold sensitive hypomorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred from genetic evidence to have normal activity at high temperatures (permissive temperatures) but to make a gene product with normal function but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity at lower temperatures (non-permissive temperatures). The genetic evidence must consist of an observation extra copies in the genome decrease the expressivity and/or penetrance of the phenotype at non-permissive temperatures. Most commonly this evidence takes the form of experiments showing that the homozygote (2 copies) has a weaker phenotype at non-permissive temperatures than the allele in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy)).

label.value: heat sensitive hypomorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred from genetic evidence to have normal activity at low temperatures (permissive temperatures) but to make a gene product with normal function but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity at higher temperatures (non-permissive temperatures). The genetic evidence must consist of an observation extra copies in the genome decrease the expressivity and/or penetrance of the phenotype at non-permissive temperatures. Most commonly this evidence takes the form of experiments showing that the homozygote (2 copies) has a weaker phenotype at non-permissive temperatures than the allele in trans to a deletion of the gene (1 copy)).

label.value: temperature conditional hypomorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to make a normal gene product in normal amounts at some temperatures, but at other temperatures to make a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity.

label.value: cold sensitive hypomorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to make a normal gene product in normal amounts at high temperatures, but at lower temperatures to make a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity.

label.value: heat sensitive hypomorphic allele - molecular evidence

value.value: An allele shown by molecular evidence to make a normal gene product in normal amounts at low temperatures, but at higher temperatures to make a gene product that is functionally equivalent to wild-type but in a lesser amount or with lowered activity.
An allele that makes a gene product that is antagonistic to the function of the wild-type gene product at some temperatures, but not others.
An allele that makes a gene product that is antagonistic to the function of the wild-type gene product at high temperatures, but not at lower temperatures.
An allele that makes a gene product that is antagonistic to the function of the wild-type gene product at cold temperatures, but not at higher temperatures.

label.value: temperature conditional antimorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred to make a gene product that is antagonistic to the wild-type gene product at some temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at others (permissive temperatures) from the observation that, at the non-permissive temperatures, the phenotype over a deficiency is stronger than that over a wild-type allele, which in turn is stronger than that in the presence of a duplication of the wild-type locus.

label.value: cold sensitive antimorphic allele - genetic evidence

value.value: An allele inferred to make a gene product that is antagonistic to the wild-type gene product at low temperatures (restrictive temperatures) but not at high temperatures (permissive temperatures) from the observation that, at the non-permissive temperatures, the phenotype over a deficiency is stronger than that over a wild-type allele, which in turn is stronger than that in the presence of a duplication of the wild-type locus.
